<table border=0 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=10 width=100%>
<tr>
<td>
<br>
<div align="left" class="newsbody">
  <script language="javascript" src="http://www.thesafehouse.org/articles/pagebreak.js"></script>
  <script language="javascript"><!--
  var showPageNavTop = 0;
  var showPageNavBot = 1;
  var showPageNavAll = 0;
  var PageMarker = '<!--page--\>';
  var PageContent= '<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>So if you have not heard yet, John Smedley, President of SoE (Sony Online Entertainment), has announced the development of a new MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>The kicker?<span>&nbsp; </span>It\'s free.<span>&nbsp; </span>The block?<span>&nbsp; </span>You pay $ for your levels and items.</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>At first glance, it may seem like an intelligent business move.<span>&nbsp; </span>You have this ever expanding market of paying real money for virtual material.<span>&nbsp; </span>Why not just be straight up with the consumers and say, “hey, here is anything you want in-game...for the right price.”</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>I will tell you why. First, it goes against the spirit of gaming in general and specifically the challenges and tribulations of an MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>Secondly, it represents a complete misunderstanding of the driving force behind the secondary market.</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>If you call yourself a gamer, you no doubt do so with pride.<span>&nbsp; </span>Pride which stems from your accomplishments of games be it computer games, console games, board games, card-games, etc...<span>&nbsp; </span>Your adeptness at learning them and succeeding at them.<span>&nbsp; </span>Your quickness with the controller or mouse or keyboard.<span>&nbsp; </span>Your almost prophetic understanding of your opponent be it a computer or a human.<span>&nbsp; </span>You have an appreciation for the very nature of the game and quite possibly an understanding of its underlying essence.<span>&nbsp; </span>Even if none of the above applies to you, you at least have a love of the game, and simply enjoy playing it.</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>When we consider the specific genre of the MMO, we see accomplishment leave the realms of dexterity, good hand-eye coordination, and fast reaction times.<span>&nbsp; </span>We see accomplishment more in erudition of the game world, knowledge of ones role, and strategic planning.<span>&nbsp; </span>These characteristics are best achieved through the MMO\'s natural lanes of progression.<span>&nbsp; </span>Bypassing these lanes will lead to a player with no experience or education in what he is doing, and in terms of an MMO, is forcing upon the league of professionals a subset of amateurs.<span>&nbsp; </span>This is nothing new though.<span>&nbsp; </span>Everyone knows this.<span>&nbsp; </span>But it is important in why Smedley\'s new game will fail.</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>Progression and item-acquisition is core to an MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>When your main game mechanic bypasses this idea, then you are left with a rather empty MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>We can assume in order for SoE to maintain a steady revenue stream they will price levels and items cheaply so that most anyone can afford it if they are indeed willing to pay.<span>&nbsp; </span>Furthermore, it stands to reason that mostly people who are willing to pay money will play a game where the fastest track to the top is with money.<span>&nbsp; </span>Therefore, you can only end up with a game of clones, all equal in technical power and differing only in real-world intellect.<span>&nbsp; </span>Starting to sound a bit unlike an MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>This however, brings me to my next point.</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>The relationship between those who would pay money to be über and those who would work and invest the time to be über is a one-way dependency.<span>&nbsp; </span>The driving force behind wanting to drop $ for virtual material is a) a lack of time commitment (intentional or otherwise) and b) envy.<span>&nbsp; </span>If you remove that which a spender is envious of from the equation (which you effectively do by creating such a game), you remove the desire to spend the money in the first place.<span>&nbsp; </span>You end up with a game, full of people with cash to blow, who thought they could finally be at the top without investing the time.<span>&nbsp; </span>A group who will quickly realize that there is no sense of accomplishment not only because they bought their way to success, but also because there is no one around they can tout their false success to.</font></p>\n<p class=MsoNormal><span style="FONT-SIZE:12pt"><font size=2>Perhaps I am all wrong, perhaps people will flock to this game, because it opens up some new peculiar genre of an MMO half-breed.<span>&nbsp; </span>An MMO without time requirements.<span>&nbsp; </span>I say though, no one has ever gotten good at a game without investing time.<span>&nbsp; </span>You sure wouldn\'t revel in being checkers champion of the world, if you payed God 10,000$ to make you instantly that good...would you?</font></span></p>';
  PrintArticle();
  // -->
  </script>
<noscript><div id="nojs" class="nojs"><p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>So if you have not heard yet, John Smedley, President of SoE (Sony Online Entertainment), has announced the development of a new MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>The kicker?<span>&nbsp; </span>It's free.<span>&nbsp; </span>The block?<span>&nbsp; </span>You pay $ for your levels and items.</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>At first glance, it may seem like an intelligent business move.<span>&nbsp; </span>You have this ever expanding market of paying real money for virtual material.<span>&nbsp; </span>Why not just be straight up with the consumers and say, “hey, here is anything you want in-game...for the right price.”</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>I will tell you why. First, it goes against the spirit of gaming in general and specifically the challenges and tribulations of an MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>Secondly, it represents a complete misunderstanding of the driving force behind the secondary market.</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>If you call yourself a gamer, you no doubt do so with pride.<span>&nbsp; </span>Pride which stems from your accomplishments of games be it computer games, console games, board games, card-games, etc...<span>&nbsp; </span>Your adeptness at learning them and succeeding at them.<span>&nbsp; </span>Your quickness with the controller or mouse or keyboard.<span>&nbsp; </span>Your almost prophetic understanding of your opponent be it a computer or a human.<span>&nbsp; </span>You have an appreciation for the very nature of the game and quite possibly an understanding of its underlying essence.<span>&nbsp; </span>Even if none of the above applies to you, you at least have a love of the game, and simply enjoy playing it.</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>When we consider the specific genre of the MMO, we see accomplishment leave the realms of dexterity, good hand-eye coordination, and fast reaction times.<span>&nbsp; </span>We see accomplishment more in erudition of the game world, knowledge of ones role, and strategic planning.<span>&nbsp; </span>These characteristics are best achieved through the MMO's natural lanes of progression.<span>&nbsp; </span>Bypassing these lanes will lead to a player with no experience or education in what he is doing, and in terms of an MMO, is forcing upon the league of professionals a subset of amateurs.<span>&nbsp; </span>This is nothing new though.<span>&nbsp; </span>Everyone knows this.<span>&nbsp; </span>But it is important in why Smedley's new game will fail.</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>Progression and item-acquisition is core to an MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>When your main game mechanic bypasses this idea, then you are left with a rather empty MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>We can assume in order for SoE to maintain a steady revenue stream they will price levels and items cheaply so that most anyone can afford it if they are indeed willing to pay.<span>&nbsp; </span>Furthermore, it stands to reason that mostly people who are willing to pay money will play a game where the fastest track to the top is with money.<span>&nbsp; </span>Therefore, you can only end up with a game of clones, all equal in technical power and differing only in real-world intellect.<span>&nbsp; </span>Starting to sound a bit unlike an MMO.<span>&nbsp; </span>This however, brings me to my next point.</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><font size=2>&nbsp;</font><font size=2>The relationship between those who would pay money to be über and those who would work and invest the time to be über is a one-way dependency.<span>&nbsp; </span>The driving force behind wanting to drop $ for virtual material is a) a lack of time commitment (intentional or otherwise) and b) envy.<span>&nbsp; </span>If you remove that which a spender is envious of from the equation (which you effectively do by creating such a game), you remove the desire to spend the money in the first place.<span>&nbsp; </span>You end up with a game, full of people with cash to blow, who thought they could finally be at the top without investing the time.<span>&nbsp; </span>A group who will quickly realize that there is no sense of accomplishment not only because they bought their way to success, but also because there is no one around they can tout their false success to.</font></p>
<p class=MsoNormal><span style="FONT-SIZE:12pt"><font size=2>Perhaps I am all wrong, perhaps people will flock to this game, because it opens up some new peculiar genre of an MMO half-breed.<span>&nbsp; </span>An MMO without time requirements.<span>&nbsp; </span>I say though, no one has ever gotten good at a game without investing time.<span>&nbsp; </span>You sure wouldn't revel in being checkers champion of the world, if you payed God 10,000$ to make you instantly that good...would you?</font></span></p></div></noscript>
</div>
   
       
   
   
